I see that I removed the jdt part of the stacktrac in the first example and
not the second. In all fairness I fixed that below:

On 7/19/06, Joakim Ohlrogge &lt;joakim.ohlrogge@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; The reason I started to use setUp instead of a constructor can be
&gt; illustrated by two examples, they both do the same but one of them throws an
&gt; exception from the constructor and the other throws an exception from the
&gt; setup method. I think that the exception thrown from the setup method is
&gt; slightly easier to read and looks more like you would expect a failure to
&gt; look like from withing a test. It is a subtle difference but it made me pick
&gt; setUp over constructors.
&gt;
&gt; import junit.framework.TestCase;
&gt;
&gt; public class TestSetup extends TestCase {
&gt;     public void setUp () {
&gt;         assertTrue(false);
&gt;     }
&gt;     public void testSomething() throws Exception {
&gt;
&gt;     }
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; fails with this message:
